WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.620
So, MDS is a group of heterogeneous hematological neoplasm.

00:00:06.620 --> 00:00:10.740
They're characterized by cytopenias, bone marrow dysplasia, and a variable risk for

00:00:10.740 --> 00:00:13.480
leukemic transformation.

00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:18.280
These diseases are generally considered incurable in the absence of a stem cell transplant.

00:00:18.280 --> 00:00:24.480
Unfortunately, historically, SCT has not been performed often in patients with MDS due to

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:28.720
these are generally older patients with significant comorbidity burden.

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:32.720
And also, generally, due to the risk of the procedure, it's usually reserved for patients

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:36.560
with higher risk disease or those of lower risk that have progressed.

00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:41.080
On the right side of the slide, you'll see some data from the Nakamura study, which was

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:47.180
a donor versus no donor comparison that showed benefit with stem cell transplant in MDS in

00:00:47.180 --> 00:00:49.280
older patients.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:53.360
So in order to better understand the role of stem cell transplant and the outcomes,

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:58.160
we performed a single center retrospective study spanning 2000 to 2023.

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:02.940
To evaluate trends, outcomes and prognostic factors in patients with MDS who undergo stem

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:05.520
cell transplant.

00:01:05.520 --> 00:01:06.840
This is an overview of the cohort.

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:07.840
There's a ton of data.

00:01:07.840 --> 00:01:11.400
I've done my best to show the highlights in the time that I have.

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:17.520
I'll be presenting some data with high risk MDS, where we identified about 2000 patients

00:01:17.520 --> 00:01:21.440
of which 21% underwent stem cell transplant.

00:01:21.440 --> 00:01:27.000
We also have some low risk MDS patients were about 9% underwent stem cell at some point

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:28.160
during their disease course.

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:33.800
And I'll also be talking briefly about our experience with CMML, where about 13% underwent

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:35.820
stem cell transplant.

00:01:35.820 --> 00:01:40.480
The median follow up time for each of these cohorts is over five years, and we've got

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:46.600
pretty extensive molecular data on a significant proportion of these patients.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:49.280
So this is the data in higher risk MDS patients.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:53.540
This is showing survival from stem cell transplant day zero.

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:57.840
One of the most notable findings that we found, there was no significant difference in overall

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.080
survival by age category.

00:02:00.080 --> 00:02:04.780
These are of course highly selected patients, but this just kind of goes to show that age

00:02:04.780 --> 00:02:10.980
in and of itself probably shouldn't be exclusion for stem cell transplant in MDS.

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:16.040
And one of the other very striking factors that we noticed was really TP53 status tends

00:02:16.040 --> 00:02:21.400
to be one of the strongest prognostic factors, where we see this really nice survival with

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:27.520
TP53 wild type with 69% of patients that are alive at five years.

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:32.780
The monoallelic TP53 patients, although they did generally poorly, there was this kind

00:02:32.780 --> 00:02:37.940
of plateau in survival around 20%, suggesting a subset of these patients are cured with

00:02:37.940 --> 00:02:39.700
stem cell transplant.

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:43.060
And unfortunately, the bioallelic patients had the worst outcomes with a median survival

00:02:43.060 --> 00:02:46.900
of only 6.8 months after transplant.

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:52.340
And this is some trends over time where we saw that as the observation period advanced,

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:56.880
the median age of the transplanted patients progressively increased, going from 52 years

00:02:56.880 --> 00:02:57.200
old.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:03:00.940
In the earlier period to 66 years old in the later periods.

00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:07.520
And we also noticed this progressive improvement in survival over the time periods.

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:10.320
This is some other observations that I made.

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:18.040
So the plot on the left shows the survival post transplant stratified by pre-transplant

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:19.040
therapy.

00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:22.900
In order to make this clean, I selected patients who proceeded to transplant after a single

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:24.900
line of therapy.

00:03:24.900 --> 00:03:26.880
We saw here that there was no difference between the untreated patients.

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:30.120
And the HMA treated patients.

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:33.520
Of course, these are different patient groups.

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:38.020
They have different baseline characteristics, so difficult to make a definitive conclusion,

00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:41.440
but we do see interesting things here that the patients who got intensive chemotherapy

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:43.200
did it quite well.

00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:47.640
These were, of course, younger patients and enriched for more favorable disease biology.

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:51.260
The curve I find the most interesting here is the patients who got the venetoclax based

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:53.440
therapy.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:56.560
There's a shorter follow up in these patients and the numbers are small.

00:03:56.560 --> 00:04:01.560
But this data looks very encouraging for that curve, potentially suggesting that deeper

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:07.900
response with venetoclax based therapy lead to better post transplant outcomes.

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:13.320
And on the right here, we see the survival stratified by the immediate blast percentage

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:19.140
before transplant, where we see there's no difference between 0 to 4% and 5 to 9%.

00:04:19.140 --> 00:04:23.780
But those with 10 or more percent blast, they seem to do worse.

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:26.240
This is a multivariate analysis.

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:31.040
Looking at factors associated with OS and high risk MDS post transplant, we see the

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:37.020
most important factor, again, here was the P53 status, but also IPSS are very high risk

00:04:37.020 --> 00:04:41.840
and HTCI were prognostic.

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:47.340
These are landmark analyses that are stratified by TP53 status.

00:04:47.340 --> 00:04:51.400
The landmark is the median time to stem cell transplant, and I also excluded patients in

00:04:51.400 --> 00:04:55.920
the control group that were over age 77.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:59.840
So, this is just a very fair comparison possible, although landmark analyses are always difficult.

00:04:59.840 --> 00:05:05.140
And here we see again, this very marked benefit in the P53 wild type, whereas the benefits

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:09.660
are much more modest than the P53 mutated patients.

00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:13.020
Even though in the biallelic ones, there's a statistically significant improvement in

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:19.080
survival, it's only about two months, so in absolute terms, that's quite low.

00:05:19.080 --> 00:05:23.900
This is just a slide on stem cell transplant lower risk MDS, this is a very difficult group

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:25.600
to study.

00:05:25.600 --> 00:05:30.160
transplant in general not perform up front in these patients. The way I looked at this is I

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:36.320
stratified the patients into the reason they went to transplant. So frontline intent to transplant,

00:05:36.460 --> 00:05:42.480
these are patients where there was a clear physician intent to transplant early. Basically,

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:47.040
they treated these patients as a high-risk patient. That group was very highly enriched

00:05:47.040 --> 00:05:52.200
in therapy-related disease. And then I looked at the patients that went to transplant for

00:05:52.200 --> 00:05:57.080
refractory cytopenia, and then those that went with blast progression, either in an MDS state

00:05:57.080 --> 00:06:01.840
or AML state, and then a clonal evolution where there was a new genetic finding that prompted

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:07.360
transplant. And what we noted here is that those that went with blast progression generally did

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:14.080
worse, where the five-year survival was in kind of the 25% range compared to the other groups where

00:06:14.080 --> 00:06:20.180
the survival was about 60%. So right now, we're looking into kind of ways to better identify

00:06:20.180 --> 00:06:22.180
patients with lower-risk MDS who potentially have MDS. So I looked at the patients that went with

00:06:22.180 --> 00:06:26.540
MDS who potentially could benefit from earlier transplant, ideally before blast progression,

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:33.940
because then they seem to do worse. This is a bit of data on CMML. The plot on the left is

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:42.500
showing survival by their disease state at the time of transplant. So statistically, similar

00:06:42.500 --> 00:06:46.860
outcomes if they're in the CMML state or secondary AML state, although numerically, the secondary

00:06:46.860 --> 00:06:51.900
AMLs did worse. And then on the right side, we see there was no difference between proliferative and

00:06:52.160 --> 00:07:00.460
plastic-type CMML. This is a multivariate of prognostic factors in CMML. Here, we noted a bit

00:07:00.460 --> 00:07:05.420
of a different story compared to MDS, where really here, it seems the RAS pathway mutations seem to be

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:12.260
one of the strongest prognostic factors. So that's mutations in KRAS, NRAS, HRAS, but also PTPN11,

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:18.740
NF1, SIBL, and BRAF, where patients without any of these mutations did extremely well post-transplant

00:07:18.740 --> 00:07:21.440
with a median survival that was not reached.

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:27.940
And then I did some landmark analyses, also stratified by RAS pathway mutation,

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:32.060
where we see that both groups derived the benefit from stem cell transplant,

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:37.740
although the benefit was much more marked in the RAS unmutated patients.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:44.000
So in conclusion, SCT is an effective therapy in high-risk MDS, being curative in close to 70%

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:50.240
of P53 wild-type patients. Over time, we noticed that it's being offered to older patients with

00:07:50.240 --> 00:07:52.140
improving outcomes over time. And then we noticed that it's being offered to older patients with

00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:55.940
I think we need some alternative or modified approaches in P53 disease.

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:02.400
The optimal timing of transplant low-risk MDS remains undefined. I think looking at dynamic

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:06.620
risk scores that could better allow us to select patients for this would be helpful.

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:10.800
And then in CMML, it looks like the RAS pathway mutations are kind of

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:14.020
one of the strongest determinants of outcome. Thank you.
